SKILL|manim-video|"Manim CE animations: 3Blue1Brown math/algo videos."
STEP|1|Before writing a single line of code**, articulate the narrative arc. What misconception does this correct? What is the "aha moment"? What visual story takes the viewer from confusion to understanding
STEP|2|Geometry before algebra.** Show the shape first, the equation second. Visual memory encodes faster than symbolic memory. When the viewer sees the geometric pattern before the formula, the equation fee
STEP|3|First-render excellence is non-negotiable.** The output must be visually clear and aesthetically cohesive without revision rounds. If something looks cluttered, poorly timed, or like "AI-generated sli
STEP|4|Opacity layering directs attention.** Never show everything at full brightness. Primary elements at 1.0, contextual elements at 0.4, structural elements (axes, grids) at 0.15. The brain processes visu
STEP|5|Breathing room.** Every animation needs `self.wait()` after it. The viewer needs time to absorb what just appeared. Never rush from one animation to the next. A 2-second pause after a key reveal is ne
STEP|6|Cohesive visual language.** All scenes share a color palette, consistent typography sizing, matching animation speeds. A technically correct video where every scene uses random different colors is an 
STEP|7|**PLAN** — Write `plan.md` with narrative arc, scene list, visual elements, color palette, voiceover script
STEP|8|**CODE** — Write `script.py` with one class per scene, each independently renderable
STEP|9|**RENDER** — `manim -ql script.py Scene1 Scene2 ...` for draft, `-qh` for production
STEP|10|**STITCH** — ffmpeg concat of scene clips into `final.mp4`
STEP|11|**AUDIO** (optional) — Add voiceover and/or background music via ffmpeg. See `references/rendering.md`
STEP|12|**REVIEW** — Render preview stills, verify against plan, adjust
STEP|13|Use monospace fonts for all text.** Manim's Pango renderer produces broken kerning with proportional fonts at all sizes. See `references/visual-design.md` for full recommendations.
STEP|14|**Different dominant color** from the palette
STEP|15|**Different layout** — don't always center everything
STEP|16|**Different animation entry** — vary between Write, FadeIn, GrowFromCenter, Create
STEP|17|**Different visual weight** — some scenes dense, others sparse
STEP|18|**Subtitles** on every animation: `self.add_subcaption("text", duration=N)` or `subcaption="text"` on `self.play()`
STEP|19|**Shared color constants** at file top for cross-scene consistency
STEP|20|**`self.camera.background_color`** set in every scene
STEP|21|**Clean exits** — FadeOut all mobjects at scene end: `self.play(FadeOut(Group(*self.mobjects)))`
STEP|22|**SCAMPER** — when the user wants a fresh take on a standard explanation
STEP|23|**Assumption Reversal** — when the user wants to challenge how something is typically taught
STEP|24|**Substitute**: replace the standard visual metaphor (number line → winding path, matrix → city grid)
STEP|25|**Combine**: merge two explanation approaches (algebraic + geometric simultaneously)
STEP|26|**Reverse**: derive backward — start from the result and deconstruct to axioms
STEP|27|**Modify**: exaggerate a parameter to show why it matters (10x the learning rate, 1000x the sample size)
STEP|28|**Eliminate**: remove all notation — explain purely through animation and spatial relationships
STEP|29|List what's "standard" about how this topic is visualized (left-to-right, 2D, discrete steps, formal notation)
STEP|30|Pick the most fundamental assumption
STEP|31|Reverse it (right-to-left derivation, 3D embedding of a 2D concept, continuous morphing instead of steps, zero notation)
STEP|32|Explore what the reversal reveals that the standard approach hides
